GOVERNOR‑Ω — FAILURE MODES

Unified Specification — Rev Ω.1

The Governor‑Ω enforces behavioural safety by halting, blocking, or stabilising output when invariants are violated.
Failure modes are deterministic, reproducible, and invariant‑safe.

Each failure mode includes:

• reason
• violated invariant(s)
• location
• lineage
• suggested fallback
• severity

The Governor must never hide or soften failures.

---

1. GOVERNOR_PREBLOCK

Triggered during the Intake Filter stage.

Conditions:

• tone instability
• behavioural drift
• recursion detected early
• unsafe expansion detected early
• emotionalisation detected
• domain mismatch
• early hallucination signals

Output:

• PREBLOCK flag
• reason
• lineage
• recommended stabilisation

This is a soft stop — stabilisation may still be possible.

---

2. GOVERNOR_BLOCK

Triggered by the Constraint Engine when a behavioural invariant fails.

Causes:

• drift
• structural rewrite
• re‑abstraction
• domain drift
• hallucination
• unsupported inference
• tone shift
• emotionalisation
• unsafe expansion
• recursive loops
• contradiction with Ω‑Core

Output:

• BLOCK flag
• violated invariant(s)
• reason
• lineage
• fallback suggestion

This is a hard stop — output cannot proceed without correction.

---

3. GOVERNOR_HALT

Triggered by the Blocker subsystem.

Conditions:

• multiple invariants violated
• correction impossible
• stabilisation unsafe
• Core contradiction
• domain reasoning unstable
• recursion or expansion exceeds limits
• global safety constraints violated

Output:

• HALT
• reason
• severity
• lineage
• NO_VALID_OUTPUT

This is the final stop.
Nothing overrides a HALT.

---

4. GOVERNOR_UNSTABLE

Triggered when output is valid but behaviourally unstable.

Causes:

• tone wobble
• verbosity drift
• borderline expansion
• minor behavioural inconsistencies
• near‑threshold recursion
• borderline domain leakage

Output:

• UNSTABLE flag
• reason
• stabilisation required

This is resolved by the Stabiliser subsystem.

---

5. GOVERNOR_UNSAFE_OUTPUT

Triggered when output is logically valid but behaviourally unsafe.

Examples:

• ambiguous phrasing
• misleading tone
• unclear safety boundaries
• content that could be misinterpreted
• borderline hallucination risk

Output:

• UNSAFE_OUTPUT
• reason
• required stabilisation

This is a behavioural safety failure, not a reasoning failure.

---

6. GOVERNOR_COMPLIANCE_FAILURE

Triggered when output violates global safety or compliance constraints.

Examples:

• unsafe recommendations
• harmful implications
• non‑neutral framing
• content violating global safety rules

Output:

• COMPLIANCE_FAILURE
• reason
• severity
• lineage

This is a high‑severity failure.

---

7. GOVERNOR_TRACEABILITY_FAILURE

Triggered when output cannot be traced back to:

• VORIN
• SERA
• AERION
• Domain Modules
• Ω‑Core

Causes:

• missing lineage
• unbacked content
• partial hallucination
• unsupported inference

Output:

• TRACEABILITY_FAILURE
• missing lineage details
• required correction

---

